comments:
#poorcustomerservice
#productreview
#productfail

Here is brand you do NOT want to buy. 

I bought not just one but TWO Sharper Image Power Percussion Deep Tissue Massagers. Not a cheap investment, but both my son and I have chronic pain.

Both will no longer charge.  The insert in the box says NOT to return to the store with a website provided for helpâ€¦ only the website is broken and there is no other link on the website for help. So, on social media, people complained about the same exact product not working for them and the admins give them a form to fill out and send in. 

I filled out the form, provided the product numbers and provided photos of the products as asked forâ€¦ I even included the boxes and cases they came in.

The reply? Please send a receipt. Bank statements donâ€™t count. Gifts must have a receipt. Why ask us for the pictures and product number  information on the form but not mention a receipt? And once the company receives the information, they infact have no intentions of helping. I can almost guarantee that if I had a receipt, they still would not plan to help. Not only is this product expensive but cheaply made, their customer service is terrible. 

Please, donâ€™t support shady companies. Additionally, I will be informing @costco about the poor product and service and I hope they stop doing business with
@sharpertomorrow_au @sharperimageofficial @asharpertomorrow 
 A Sharper Tomorrow. 

My experience with Costco is that they value their customers, and have no hassle returns or exchanges. I wish I could say the same about Sharper Image.

An expensive product should last a few years at the minimum, not a few months.

comments:
I am writing to express my disappointment regarding a recent experience at one of your locations. As a loyal Costco member, I was surprised and frustrated to learn that my son was denied entry while attempting to shop on my behalf, despite presenting my valid membership card.

On that particular day, I was unwell and unable to visit the store myself, so I entrusted my son with my membership card to purchase essential items. However, your staff refused to allow him entry, stating that the card could only be used by the actual member. While I understand the importance of maintaining membership integrity, I find this policy to be unnecessarily rigid and impractical in situations like mine.

Many other retailers allow family members to shop on behalf of the primary member, especially when there is no fraudulent intent. Costcoâ€™s strict enforcement of this rule seems unreasonable and creates unnecessary inconvenience for paying members. It would be more customer-friendly if Costco considered making reasonable exceptions, particularly in cases where a family member is simply helping due to illness or other valid reasons.

I hope you take this feedback into consideration and revisit this policy to better serve your members.
